<h2 id="cfp">Call for Papers (<a href="http://www.sleconf.org/2017/CFP.html">source</a>, 35 taggings)</h2>
<p>
</p>
<h3>Topics of Interest</h3>
<p>
</p>
<p>SLE aims to be broad-minded and inclusive about relevance and scope. We solicit high-quality contributions in areas ranging from theoretical and conceptual contributions to tools, techniques, and frameworks in the domain of language engineering. Topics relevant to SLE cover generic aspects of software languages development rather than aspects of engineering a specific language. In particular, SLE is interested in principled engineering approaches and techniques in the following areas:
</p>
<p>
</p>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Language Design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span> and Implementation</li>
<ul>
<li>Approaches and methodologies for <span class="term">language design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Static semantics</span><span class="tag" title="T1B: Static Semantics"><a href="../tag/t1b.html">T1B</a></span> (e.g., design rules, well-formedness constraints)</li>
<li>Techniques for <span class="term">behavioral / executable semantics</span><span class="tag" title="T1C: Behavioural Semantics"><a href="../tag/t1c.html">T1C</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Generative approaches</span><span class="tag" title="T4C: Vertical Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4c.html">T4C</a></span> (incl. <span class="term">code synthesis</span><span class="tag" title="T4C: Vertical Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4c.html">T4C</a></span>, compilation)</li>
<li>Meta-languages, <span class="term">meta-tools</span><span class="tag" title="T4A: Workbenches"><a href="../tag/t4a.html">T4A</a></span>, <span class="term">language workbenches</span><span class="tag" title="T4A: Workbenches"><a href="../tag/t4a.html">T4A</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Language Validation</span><span class="tag" title="T5D: Formal Methods"><a href="../tag/t5d.html">T5D</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Verification and formal methods for languages</span><span class="tag" title="T5D: Formal Methods"><a href="../tag/t5d.html">T5D</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Testing techniques for languages</span><span class="tag" title="T5C: Testing"><a href="../tag/t5c.html">T5C</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Simulation techniques for languages</span><span class="tag" title="T4E: Simulation"><a href="../tag/t4e.html">T4E</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Language Integration and Composition</span><span class="tag" title="T1D: Composition"><a href="../tag/t1d.html">T1D</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Coordination</span><span class="tag" title="T1D: Composition"><a href="../tag/t1d.html">T1D</a></span> of heterogeneous languages and tools</li>
<li><span class="term">Mappings</span><span class="tag" title="T4B: Horizontal Transformation"><a href="../tag/t4b.html">T4B</a></span> between languages (incl. <span class="term">transformation languages</span><span class="tag" title="T3B: Transformation Languages"><a href="../tag/t3b.html">T3B</a></span>)</li>
<li><span class="term">Traceability between languages</span><span class="tag" title="T5G: Traceability"><a href="../tag/t5g.html">T5G</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Deployment of languages to different platforms</span><span class="tag" title="T2D: Deployment"><a href="../tag/t2d.html">T2D</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Language Maintenance</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span></li>
<ul>
<li><span class="term">Software language reuse</span><span class="tag" title="T1E: Reuse"><a href="../tag/t1e.html">T1E</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Language evolution</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span></li>
<li><span class="term">Language families and variability</span><span class="tag" title="T2C: Variability"><a href="../tag/t2c.html">T2C</a></span></li>
</ul>
<li><span class="term">Domain-specific approaches</span><span class="tag" title="T3C: DSLs"><a href="../tag/t3c.html">T3C</a></span> for any aspects of SLE (<span class="term">design</span><span class="tag" title="T1A: Design"><a href="../tag/t1a.html">T1A</a></span>, implementation, <span class="term">validation</span><span class="tag" title="T5D: Formal Methods"><a href="../tag/t5d.html">T5D</a></span>, <span class="term">maintenance</span><span class="tag" title="T2B: Evolution"><a href="../tag/t2b.html">T2B</a></span>)</li>
<li><span class="term">Empirical evaluation</span><span class="tag" title="T5E: Empirical Evaluation"><a href="../tag/t5e.html">T5E</a></span> and <span class="term">experience reports</span><span class="tag" title="T6A: Experience Reports"><a href="../tag/t6a.html">T6A</a></span> of language engineering tools - <span class="term">User studies</span><span class="tag" title="T5E: Empirical Evaluation"><a href="../tag/t5e.html">T5E</a></span> evaluating <span class="term">usability</span><span class="tag" title="T5H: Usability"><a href="../tag/t5h.html">T5H</a></span> - <span class="term">Performance benchmarks</span><span class="tag" title="T5F: Performance"><a href="../tag/t5f.html">T5F</a></span> - <span class="term">Industrial applications</span><span class="tag" title="T6B: Industrial"><a href="../tag/t6b.html">T6B</a></span></li>
</ul>
<p>
</p>
<h3>Types of Submissions</h3>
<p>
</p>
<ul>
<li>Research papers: These should report a substantial research contribution to SLE or successful application of SLE techniques or both. Full paper submissions must not exceed 12 pages including bibliography.</li>
<li>Tool papers: Because of SLE’s interest in tools, we seek papers that present software tools related to the field of SLE. Selection criteria include originality of the tool, its innovative aspects, and relevance to SLE. Any of the SLE topics of interest are appropriate areas for tool demonstrations. Submissions must provide a tool description of 4 pages including bibliography, and a demonstration outline including screenshots of up to 6 pages. Tool demonstrations must have the keywords “Tool Demo” or “Tool Demonstration” in the title. The 4-page tool description will, if the demonstration is accepted, be published in the proceedings. The 6-page demonstration outline will be used by the program committee only for evaluating the submission.</li>
<li><span class="term">Industrial</span><span class="tag" title="T6B: Industrial"><a href="../tag/t6b.html">T6B</a></span> papers: These should describe <span class="term">real-world application</span><span class="tag" title="T6B: Industrial"><a href="../tag/t6b.html">T6B</a></span> scenarios of SLE in <span class="term">industry</span><span class="tag" title="T6B: Industrial"><a href="../tag/t6b.html">T6B</a></span>, explained in their context with an analysis of the challenges that were overcome and the lessons which the audience can learn from this experience. Industry paper submissions must not exceed 6 pages including bibliography.</li>
<li>New ideas / vision papers: New ideas papers should describe new, non-conventional SLE research approaches that depart from standard practice. They are intended to describe well-defined research ideas that are at an early stage of investigation. Vision papers are intended to present new unifying theories about existing SLE research that can lead to the development of new technologies or approaches. New ideas / vision papers must not exceed 4 pages including bibliography.</li>
</ul><h2 id="lop">List of Papers (1+24, <a href="https://dblp.org/db/conf/sle/sle2017.html">source</a>)</h2>
<ul class="lop">

<li><span title="Keynote">🔥</span> <em><a href="keynote1.html">Engineering meta-languages for specifying software languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/PeterDMosses.html">Peter D. Mosses</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The keynote is centrally about engineering and using meta-languages to specify the components of software languages.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL" title="It stresses formal/executable semantic specifications as a key missing piece of language definitions.">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="A major theme is how meta-language choices enable or constrain tool support for languages.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It discusses formal specification and reasoning about language definitions as a methodological foundation.">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper01.html">A development environment for the Alf language within the MagicDraw UML tool (tool demo)</a></em> (<a href="../profile/EdSeidewitz.html">Ed Seidewitz</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper presents an IDE/development environment (in MagicDraw) for the Alf action language.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It focuses on integrating a textual action language with UML models inside an existing modeling tool.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="Alf is a domain-specific action language for expressing executable behavior in UML models.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work is demonstrated in a commercial/industrial-grade modeling tool context (MagicDraw).">T6B: Industrial</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper02.html">Red Shift: procedural shift-reduce parsing (vision paper)</a></em> (<a href="../profile/NicolasLaurent.html">Nicolas Laurent</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM" title="Its core contribution is a new parsing design pattern (procedural shift-reduce parsing), i.e., runtime parsing technology.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="It connects and extends established grammar/parsing formalisms (shift-reduce and PEG-style parsing).">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="The vision explicitly targets practical parser implementation concerns such as determinism and efficiency.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL" title="It proposes language-implementation design choices for how syntactic ambiguity is resolved in practice.">T1A: Design</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper03.html">A domain-specific controlled English language for automated regulatory compliance (industrial paper)</a></em> (<a href="../profile/SumanRoychoudhury.html">Suman Roychoudhury</a>, <a href="../profile/SagarSunkle.html">Sagar Sunkle</a>, <a href="../profile/DeepaliKholkar.html">Deepali Kholkar</a>, <a href="../profile/VinayKulkarni.html">Vinay Kulkarni</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM" title="The contribution is a controlled-English DSL for expressing regulations and compliance checks.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The goal is capturing regulatory compliance requirements precisely enough for automated checking.">T5A: Requirements</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL" title="It is positioned as an industrial paper driven by enterprise compliance needs.">T6B: Industrial</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3e.html"><span class="tagL" title="The approach aligns with knowledge/meaning modeling for regulations, bordering on ontology-style representations.">T3E: Ontologies</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper04.html">Better call the crowd: using crowdsourcing to shape the notation of domain-specific languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MarcoBrambilla.html">Marco Brambilla</a>, <a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a>, <a href="../profile/JavierLuisCánovasIzquierdo.html">Javier Luis Cánovas Izquierdo</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreaMauri.html">Andrea Mauri</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper’s main aim is improving usability/acceptance of DSML notations by involving end-users via crowdsourcing.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL" title="It directly concerns the design of a language’s notation (concrete syntax) informed by user feedback.">T1A: Design</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title="Crowdsourcing implies empirical collection and analysis of user preferences over notational alternatives.">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The setting is domain-specific modeling languages whose notations are being designed.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper05.html">Comparison of the expressiveness and performance of template-based code generation tools</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LechanceuxLuhunu.html">Lechanceux Luhunu</a>, <a href="../profile/EugeneSyriani.html">Eugene Syriani</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM" title="It compares template-based code generation tools, i.e., generative compilation/code synthesis from models.">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="A central evaluation dimension is performance of code generation approaches.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title="The paper empirically compares tools on expressiveness and performance across scenarios/benchmarks.">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The subject of comparison is tooling infrastructure used in language/workbench-based generation workflows.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper06.html">FlowSpec: declarative dataflow analysis specification</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JeffSmits.html">Jeff Smits</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM" title="FlowSpec is a DSL for specifying dataflow analyses over programming languages.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Dataflow analyses are classic static-semantics analyses, and the DSL is for declaring such analyses.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="It plays the role of a meta-language for describing analyses over language control-flow graphs.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work includes language-engineering infrastructure for defining CFGs and running the specified analyses.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper07.html">A chrestomathy of DSL implementations</a></em> (<a href="../profile/SimonSchauss.html">Simon Schauss</a>, <a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/JohannesHärtel.html">Johannes Härtel</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcelHeinz.html">Marcel Heinz</a>, <a href="../profile/KevinKlein.html">Kevin Klein</a>, <a href="../profile/LukasHärtel.html">Lukas Härtel</a>, <a href="../profile/ThorstenBerger.html">Thorsten Berger</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t2e.html"><span class="tagM" title="The main artifact is a well-documented chrestomathy/collection (MetaLib) intended to teach and document DSL implementation approaches.">T2E: Documentation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL" title="MetaLib is explicitly structured to enable reuse of DSL implementation patterns and components across examples.">T1E: Reuse</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The subject matter is implementing domain-specific languages using multiple approaches.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The contribution includes a supporting software repository/tooling for browsing and using the chrestomathy.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper08.html">A symbol-based extension of parsing expression grammars and context- sensitive packrat parsing</a></em> (<a href="../profile/KimioKuramitsu.html">Kimio Kuramitsu</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper extends PEG-based parsing with context-sensitive capabilities, i.e., runtime parsing/recognition techniques.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="PEGs are treated as a grammar formalism, and the work extends that meta-language with symbol-based mechanisms.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It targets modular recognition of patterns found in real languages, including composition-like idioms (e.g., typedef-style contexts).">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="Context-sensitive packrat parsing raises efficiency concerns that the paper addresses as part of practicality.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper09.html">Concrete syntax: a multi-paradigm modelling approach</a></em> (<a href="../profile/YentlVanTendeloo.html">Yentl Van Tendeloo</a>, <a href="../profile/SimonVanMierlo.html">Simon Van Mierlo</a>, <a href="../profile/BartMeyers.html">Bart Meyers</a>, <a href="../profile/HansVangheluwe.html">Hans Vangheluwe</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM" title="It proposes a multi-paradigm approach to defining concrete syntax, i.e., language design of notations.">T1A: Design</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work is motivated by domain-specific modeling languages and how their syntax is defined.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL" title="Concrete syntax work typically spans visual/textual notations, and the paper explicitly targets multi-paradigm (incl. visual) syntax.">T4F: Visualisation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It emphasizes coordinating multiple syntactic paradigms for the same language, requiring integration between notation forms.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper10.html">Energy efficiency across programming languages: how do energy, time, and memory relate?</a></em> (<a href="../profile/RuiPereira.html">Rui Pereira</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcoCouto.html">Marco Couto</a>, <a href="../profile/FranciscoRibeiro.html">Francisco Ribeiro</a>, <a href="../profile/RuiRua.html">Rui Rua</a>, <a href="../profile/JácomeCunha.html">Jácome Cunha</a>, <a href="../profile/JoãoPauloFernandes.html">João Paulo Fernandes</a>, <a href="../profile/JoãoSaraiva.html">João Saraiva</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM" title="This is an empirical study measuring energy, time, and memory across many programming languages.">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The comparison spans general-purpose programming languages as the primary objects of study.">T3D: GPLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="It analyzes performance-related dimensions (runtime and memory) alongside energy consumption.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It bridges programming languages with energy/performance measurement methodology, a cross-area synergy.">T6D: Synergies</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper11.html">Ensuring non-interference of composable language extensions</a></em> (<a href="../profile/TedKaminski.html">Ted Kaminski</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper is about composing independent language extensions and ensuring they do not interfere.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Non-interference properties are framed and justified with formal criteria/arguments.">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Guaranteeing extension safety often relies on static checks (e.g., typing/discipline) that the paper builds on.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The setting typically assumes compiler construction mechanisms for combining extensions into an executable toolchain.">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper12.html">Metacasanova: an optimized meta-compiler for domain-specific languages</a></em> (<a href="../profile/FrancescoDiGiacomo.html">Francesco Di Giacomo</a>, <a href="../profile/MohamedAbbadi.html">Mohamed Abbadi</a>, <a href="../profile/AgostinoCortesi.html">Agostino Cortesi</a>, <a href="../profile/PieterSpronck.html">Pieter Spronck</a>, <a href="../profile/GiuseppeMaggiore.html">Giuseppe Maggiore</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM" title="Metacasanova is a meta-compiler for DSLs, focusing on compilation/code generation pipelines.">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="It targets domain-specific languages and their efficient compilation.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="The contribution emphasizes optimization and efficiency of the generated artifacts/toolchain.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="As a meta-compiler, it is tooling infrastructure for implementing DSLs.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper13.html">Towards a taxonomy of grammar smells</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MatsStijlaart.html">Mats Stijlaart</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title="It proposes a taxonomy of grammar smells, i.e., systematic analysis of grammar/language descriptions.">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Grammar smells are motivated by grammar refactoring and maintenance of evolving language definitions.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The objects analyzed are grammars, which are meta-language artifacts used to define syntax.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="A taxonomy supports building analysis/refactoring tools for grammars, which the paper discusses as a motivation.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper14.html">A formalisation of parameterised reference attribute grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/ScottBuckley.html">Scott Buckley</a>, <a href="../profile/AnthonyMSloane.html">Anthony M. Sloane</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper formalizes parameterised reference attribute grammars as a meta-language formalism.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Its main contribution is a formalisation enabling equivalence/correctness-style reasoning about attribute-grammar systems.">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Reference attribute grammars are widely used to define static semantic analyses in language implementations.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Parameterisation is aimed at modular reuse/composition of attribute-grammar components across language fragments.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper15.html">Concurrent circular reference attribute grammars</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JesperÖqvist.html">Jesper Öqvist</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM" title="It focuses on concurrent evaluation of circular reference attribute grammars, i.e., runtime interpretation/execution of semantic specifications.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="Reference attribute grammars are the underlying meta-language/formalism whose execution is optimized.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="The paper’s motivation and results revolve around latency/throughput improvements via concurrency.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Attribute-grammar evaluation computes static semantic information, and concurrency changes how that semantic computation is executed.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper16.html">Debugging with domain-specific events via macros</a></em> (<a href="../profile/XiangqiLi.html">Xiangqi Li</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthewFlatt.html">Matthew Flatt</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The core contribution is debugging/tool support so that DSL users can debug in terms of domain-specific events.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It relies on embedding DSL surface syntax via macros into a host language and mapping back during debugging.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Domain-specific debugging depends on runtime event reporting and execution-time instrumentation.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="The aim is to improve the developer experience by making debugging feedback align with DSL-level concepts.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper17.html">Deep priority conflicts in the wild: a pilot study</a></em> (<a href="../profile/LuísEduardodeSouzaAmorim.html">Luís Eduardo de Souza Amorim</a>, <a href="../profile/MichaelJSteindorfer.html">Michael J. Steindorfer</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM" title="It is a pilot study of deep priority conflicts found in real-world grammars.">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL" title="The subject matter is analysis of grammar specifications to identify and characterize conflicts.">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Such conflicts motivate grammar refactoring and long-term maintenance of language definitions.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The analyzed artifacts are context-free grammars, i.e., meta-language descriptions of syntax.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper18.html">Incremental packrat parsing</a></em> (<a href="../profile/PatrickDubroy.html">Patrick Dubroy</a>, <a href="../profile/AlessandroWarth.html">Alessandro Warth</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper turns packrat parsing into an incremental parser, a runtime parsing technique for interactive settings.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL" title="Incrementality is pursued to improve performance when repeatedly parsing small edits.">T5F: Performance</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="Incremental parsing is primarily motivated by editor/IDE tooling that needs fast feedback.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="Packrat parsing is tied to PEG-style grammar formalisms, which serve as the underlying meta-language.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper19.html">Robust programs with filtered iterators</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JiasiShen.html">Jiasi Shen</a>, <a href="../profile/MartinCRinard.html">Martin C. Rinard</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM" title="It introduces a new language construct (filtered iterators) for robust input processing.">T1A: Design</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL" title="Robust input processing is realized through runtime iteration/filtering behavior during execution.">T4D: Interpretation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="The construct is motivated by reducing common programmer errors and improving comprehensibility of input-handling code.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL" title="The contribution is framed as a construct for general-purpose programming languages rather than a narrow DSL.">T3D: GPLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper20.html">Robust projectional editing</a></em> (<a href="../profile/FriedrichSteimann.html">Friedrich Steimann</a>, <a href="../profile/MarcusFrenkel.html">Marcus Frenkel</a>, <a href="../profile/MarkusVölter.html">Markus Völter</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper addresses projectional editor technology and how to make projectional editing more robust.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="It emphasizes enforcing well-formedness rules (static constraints) in addition to metamodel conformance.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="A key goal is improving user experience by preventing/handling ill-formed intermediate states during editing.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It discusses how editing constraints interact with composed language fragments and their well-formedness rules.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper21.html">Structural model subtyping with OCL constraints</a></em> (<a href="../profile/ArturBoronat.html">Artur Boronat</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM" title="The main contribution is a static semantics notion of structural model subtyping constrained by OCL.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title="It develops formal conditions/definitions for subtyping and constraint satisfaction.">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL" title="Subtyping is motivated by enabling flexible reuse of models and transformations across related model types.">T1E: Reuse</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The setting is model-driven engineering where models and constraints form a domain-specific modeling language.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper22.html">Type-safe modular parsing</a></em> (<a href="../profile/HaoyuanZhang.html">Haoyuan Zhang</a>, <a href="../profile/HuangLi.html">Huang Li</a>, <a href="../profile/BrunoCdSOliveira.html">Bruno C. d. S. Oliveira</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The focus is modular parsing—supporting extensibility and separate compilation of parsers for language fragments.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Type safety is a first-class requirement, so the approach relies on static guarantees about composed parsers.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="Modular parsing is motivated by and applicable to building scalable language tooling (parsers) in workbenches.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work assumes grammar-like specifications for fragments, treating parsing interfaces as meta-language artifacts.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper23.html">Virtual textual model composition for supporting versioning and aspect-orientation</a></em> (<a href="../profile/RobertBill.html">Robert Bill</a>, <a href="../profile/PatrickNeubauer.html">Patrick Neubauer</a>, <a href="../profile/ManuelWimmer.html">Manuel Wimmer</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper’s core topic is composing textual models virtually to support versioning and aspect-oriented separation.">T1D: Composition</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="It is motivated by maintenance tasks and versioning scenarios where code/model redundancy and irrelevance hinder evolution.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Virtual composition entails mapping/synchronizing between base artifacts and composed virtual views.">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="It targets improved developer cognition by hiding redundancy/irrelevance in composed views (usability for maintenance).">T5H: Usability</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper24.html">A requirements engineering approach for usability-driven DSL development ANKICA BARIŠIĆ, NOVA University of Lisbon, Lisbon, Lisboa, Portugal</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AnkicaBarišić.html">Ankica Barišić</a>, <a href="../profile/DominiqueBlouin.html">Dominique Blouin</a>, <a href="../profile/VascoAmaral.html">Vasco Amaral</a>, <a href="../profile/MiguelGoulão.html">Miguel Goulão</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t5a.html"><span class="tagM" title="It proposes a requirements engineering approach specifically for developing DSLs.">T5A: Requirements</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL" title="Usability is an explicit driver for eliciting and prioritizing DSL requirements.">T5H: Usability</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title="The approach is tailored to domain-specific languages and their development process.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="It frames DSL development as an evolving lifecycle activity where requirements drive iterative refinement.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
</li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="org">Organisers</h2><ul><li><a href="../profile/BenoîtCombemale.html">Benoît Combemale</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-papers-organizing-committee">General Chair</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/MarjanMernik.html">Marjan Mernik</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-papers-organizing-committee">Programme Chair</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-papers-organizing-committee">Programme Chair</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/MarjanMernik.html">Marjan Mernik</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/ChristianBerger.html">Christian Berger</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/MarkvandenBrand.html">Mark van den Brand</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/RuthBreu.html">Ruth Breu</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/JordiCabot.html">Jordi Cabot</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/WalterCazzola.html">Walter Cazzola</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/MarshaChechik.html">Marsha Chechik</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/TonyClark.html">Tony Clark</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/TomDinkelaker.html">Tom Dinkelaker</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/SébastienGérard.html">Sébastien Gérard</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/JeffreyGGray.html">Jeffrey G. Gray</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/EstherGuerra.html">Esther Guerra</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/MichaelHomer.html">Michael Homer</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/TihamérLevendovszky.html">Tihamér Levendovszky</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/GunterMussbacher.html">Gunter Mussbacher</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/TerenceParr.html">Terence Parr</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">PC</a>)</li><li><a href="../profile/JaroslavPorubän.html">Jaroslav Porubän</a> (<a href="https://conf.researchr.org/committee/sle-2017/sle-2017-sle-2017-organizing-committee">